article.description: Elbows were flying, and so were the technical fouls. Phoenix's Diana Taurasi was involved  directly or indirectly  in all four Ts as Washington won, 77-56.
article.headline: Mercury's Taurasi involved in four technicals
article.linkText: Technically speaking, Mystics cool off Phoenix
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- An ugly night in the WNBA was a split-second
away from an all-out melee. Diana Taurasi was being rushed at
midcourt by DeLisha Milton-Jones, who was fed up with what she said
was the latest cheap shot from one of the league's marquee players.

Milton-Jones' teammate, Chasity Melvin, intervened before a blow
could be landed. After the game, there were accusations of dirty
play, and one coach complained that the refs decided the game.

The Washington Mystics beat the Phoenix Mercury 77-56 Tuesday
night, and good sportsmanship finished a distant third.

"During the course of the game, they were getting some cheap
shots," Milton-Jones said. "This is what happened: After you make
a shot, and you're running back to go on defense, somebody will run
and just stop and give you a shoulder -- and that's blindside. You
can't see it. You can't change directions to prevent it from
happening. I'm not going to tolerate that."

With 1:44 to go in the game, Milton-Jones said it happened
again, with Taurasi lowering her shoulder as they headed downcourt.
Milton-Jones hit the deck, then got up and ran after Taurasi.
Melvin got between them, but both players were given technicals.
Milton-Jones was ejected.

"I reacted. I know I could have reacted differently, but my
emotions got the best of me," said Milton-Jones, who then
apologized to her teammates and fans.

Meanwhile, in the other locker room, Taurasi pleaded total
innocence.

"She ran straight into me and fell. That's all I can get from
it," Taurasi said.

Asked if she was surprised by Milton-Jones' reaction, Taurasi
said: "No, that's DeLisha. That's what you're going to get from
her. I'm not going to back down. This team's not going to back
down. If she wants to come after people, we're going to be right
there. ... It's a good thing she didn't get to me."

But Milton-Jones went even further, implying that Taurasi's
actions were malicious and a possible reaction to the Mercury's
struggles. After winning virtually every game she played at the
University of Connecticut, Taurasi is on a 3-8 team in her second
WNBA season.

"She's so used to winning," Milton-Jones said. "It's an
unfortunate situation that she has to be in, but you can still grow
as a player no matter what situation it is. Me, I come from LA to
the Washington Mystics. We were 1-3 the first couple of games. I'm
usually 9-0, but that doesn't mean I have to go out and be
malicious in my actions. Learn to grow as a person and as a
player."

Milton-Jones said she wants to address the matter directly with
Taurasi.

"I really do want to want to talk to her because it's not just
for me, it's for the next man," Milton-Jones said. "She may hurt
somebody. It may end their career. She has to look at it from that
aspect."

Taurasi was definitely the center of attention throughout the
game. She was involved -- directly or indirectly -- in all four
technical fouls in a very physical second half.

First, when Taurasi drew a foul backing in on Temeka Johnson,
Mystics coach Richie Adubato called timeout and walked halfway
across the court to yell at an official, drawing a technical.

A few minutes later, Taurasi threw elbows to knock down two
Mystics players after grabbing a rebound. Taurasi was given an
offensive foul, and coach Carrie Graf was given a technical for
arguing.

Then, after the Mystics had taken control of the game, Taurasi
and Milton-Jones had their altercation.

"It happened with Plenette Pierson in the first half, and then
the same thing happen with Diana," said Alana Beard, holding an
ice pack over a welt next to her eye in the Mystics locker room.
"They wait until we run down the court full speed, and then they
step in the way on purpose. I saw it coming. I can't say that I
blame DeLisha, but in a way we've got to keep our composure."

Meanwhile, Graf and Taurasi had a different beef. They were
upset by the second-half 15-6 foul differential that favored the
Mystics. Graf transposed the numbers, but she got her point across.

"When it's that physical and that competitive on the glass and
one team gets 16 fouls and one team gets five, that makes it hard
to be in the game," the coach said.

Beard finished with 19 points to lead the Mystics (5-6), who
have their first winning streak of the season. They have also won
four straight at home.

Anna DeForge scored 18 points and Taurasi added 16 for the
Mercury, but 30 of their combined 34 points came in the first half.
Taurasi was 1-for-4 from the field with four points in the volatile
second half.

"It's frustrating when you can't get a call the whole night,
when nothing's going right," Taurasi said.
